Overplotting

Notes: - Some of the points, towards the bottom are so closely packed, we can’t really tell density - Introduce alpha component for pixel intensity (alpha = 1/x) means x points needed to make a solid point - Introduce jitter because age is not a perfect integer

ggplot(data = pf, aes(x = age, y = friend_count)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 1/20) +
  xlim(13, 90)
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 4906 rows containing missing
## values (geom_point).

ggplot(data = pf, aes(x = age, y = friend_count)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 1/20) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(13, 90), breaks = seq(10, 90, 5)) +

Coord_trans()

Notes: http://docs.ggplot2.org/current/coord_trans.html - Transform y axis to look at it better using sqrt

ggplot(data = pf, aes(x = age, y = friend_count)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 1/20) +
  xlim(13, 90) +
  coord_trans(y = "sqrt")
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 4906 rows containing missing
## values (geom_point).

#### What do you notice? Response - Didn’t work with geom_jitter(). Had to use geom_point(). - Lines became fainter close to y = 0 indicating that there are very few accounts with close to 0 friends.

Look up the documentation for coord_trans() and add a layer to the plot that transforms friend_count using the square root function with jitter. Create your plot!

Notes: - Notice that just using geom_jitter() adds jitter to friend count as well. For accounts with zero users, jitter can make friend_count -ve and sqrt(-ve) will break down

# h = 0 specifies that even after y jitter, limit min value of y to 0
ggplot(data = pf, aes(x = age, y = friend_count)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 1/20, position = position_jitter(h = 0)) +
  xlim(13, 90) +
  coord_trans(y = "sqrt")

Conditional Means

Notes: We want to be able to see measures of center variations instead of looking at each point - Since age goes all the way from 13, 90, its not a good idea to do this using boxplot or histogram for each age. (That would make it 90 different plots) - So we will transform data to calculate the mean and median of friend counts by age and use that - Think of dplyr helping in aggregation functions that we see in SQL

library('dplyr')
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## 
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter
## 
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
# Does nothing but group observations together by age
pf.by_age <- group_by(pf, age)

# NOTE that summarise() is different from summary()
pf.fc_by_age <- summarise(pf.by_age, 
                          fc_mean = mean(friend_count), 
                          fc_median = median(friend_count), 
                          n = n())

##  $ n        : int  484 1925 2618 3086 3283 5196 4391 3769 3671 3032 ...
# Note that you CANNOT pipeline data tables or databases
pf.fc_by_age <- pf %>%
  group_by(age) %>%
  summarise(fc_mean = mean(friend_count),
            fc_median = median(friend_count),
            n = n()) %>%
  arrange(age)

head(pf.fc_by_age)

Response: Note - When pipelining, we omit the data variable because dataframe is assumed to pipeline from previous stage to the next

Create your plot!

Notes: - Since we have only one data point per mean, we are NOT dealing with frequencies - This means that histograms, freqplots & boxplots are out of the question http://docs.ggplot2.org/current/geom_line.html

Overlaying Summaries with Raw Data

Notes: - Add mean, median, 10% and 90% quantiles on top of scatter plot to get a better sense of ranges - Wow, some really funky syntax. summary is in quotes, but not the function name mean!

ggplot(aes(x = age, y = friend_count), data = pf) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 1/20, position = position_jitter(h = 0), color = 'green') +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(13, 90), breaks = seq(10, 90, 5)) +
  coord_trans(y = "sqrt") +
  geom_line(stat = "summary", fun.y = mean) +
  geom_line(stat = "summary", fun.y = median, color = I('#aa88ff')) +
  geom_line(stat = "summary", fun.y = quantile, probs = 0.1, color = I('red'), linetype = 2) +
  geom_line(stat = "summary", fun.y = quantile, probs = 0.9, color = I('red'), linetype = 3)

Correlation

Notes: - Use cor.test to calculate pearson coefficient for age and friend count - From graph, we see that it is really a bell-curve relation between age & friend count - So, I am guessing pretty close to 0 or un-correlated

pearson <- cor.test(x = pf$age, y = pf$friend_count)
pearson

Look up the documentation for the cor.test function. What’s the correlation between age and friend count? Round to three decimal places.

Response: r = -0.027 Note how it is almost zero as expected.

Correlation on Subsets

Notes: - Do the same thing with data frames using with() - If we blow away the higher ages (say >65), we can expect a -ve slope line and stronger correlation

pearson2 <- with(pf, cor.test(age, friend_count, conf.level = 0.99))
pearson2
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  age and friend_count
## t = -8.6268, df = 99001, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 99 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.03558573 -0.01922535
## sample estimates:
##         cor 
## -0.02740737
p.le_65 <- with(subset(pf, age <= 65), cor.test(age, friend_count, conf.level = 0.99))
p.le_65

Moira on Correlation

Notes: - As we already noted, if we use perfectly correlated variables as features for linear regression, it will never converge on a solution. When you use matrices, inverse will not exist. - Basically need to identify and get rid of redundant features to get rid of the issue.

A New Perspective

What do you notice? Response: Temperature actually varies with month, but not linearly of course . You will notice sinusoidal pattern when you make x axis 5x the y axis in zoomed plot

Understanding Noise: Age to Age Months

Notes: You can do modulo 12 on month to see the same thing more clearly

ggplot(aes(y = Temp, x = (Month %% 12)), data = Mitchell) + 
  geom_point(color = 'blue') +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = c(0, 11), breaks = seq(0, 11, 2))

# A multivariate t-test for independence rejects null hypothesis which in this case that they are uncorrelated
# Null hypo is rejected thus proving variables are indeed correlated in some fashion
library('energy')
dcor.ttest(Mitchell$Month, Mitchell$Temp)
## 
##  dcor t-test of independence

Age with Months Means solution

pf.fc_by_age_months <- pf %>%
  group_by(age_with_months) %>%
  summarise(friend_count_mean = mean(friend_count),
            friend_count_median = median(friend_count),
            n = n()) %>%
  arrange(age_with_months)

Noise in Conditional Means

Response: This is a trade-off between bias and variance. geom_smooth handles this for you. Note however, that geom_smooth() can completely miss out on important info such as the peak at 69.

Which Plot to Choose?

Notes: Choice is based on audience and it may be good to use different plots based on story you are trying to tell

Analyzing Two Variables

Reflection: - scatter plots with geom_point() - adding jitter with geom_jitter() - using alpha for transparency to mitigate overplotting - Pipelines using dply with group_by(), summarise() and arrange() to calculate conditional means df - Overlaying mean, median and quantiles on top of scatter plots - calculating pearson’s coefficient with and doing a correlation test with cor.test() - Use correlation to not pick variables that are strongly correlated in feature set as this can lead to logistic/linear regression breaking down - multivariate ttest for independence between two variables using dcor.ttest() - conditional means plots with geom_line() after calculating a df with central measures using dply - noise and smoothing and which plots to choose
